<TITLE> Hasina meets Indian leaders, talks of regional peace </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 By Sumon Mahbub and bdnews24.com's New Delhi correspondent New Delhi, Jan 11 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh will not allow its territory to be used by terrorists under any circumstance, prime minister Sheikh Hasina has said in New Delhi. "We are a peace-loving nation. We want to establish peace in this region," Hasina said during meetings on Monday with the Indian external affairs minister, finance minister and opposition party leader. The prime minister's press secretary Abul Kalam Azal briefed journalists after the meetings on Hasina's first day of official engagements on the four-day visit. "The prime minister said the Bangladesh government will not do anything that goes against its people's interests." Hasina, who arrived in India Sunday evening, began her state visit with a ceremonial reception on Monday at the Rashtrapati Bhavan in New Delhi  the city that had also been her home between 1976 and 1981. She said Bangladesh would continue efforts with neighbours to build a stable South Asia, speaking at the reception. Hasina also stressed bilateral cooperation for the fight against poverty in both countries. "I have brought a message of friendship from the Bangladeshi people," she said. "Bangladesh will continue its effort to build a stable and prosperous South Asia." She hoped her tour of India, the first since she assumed office a year ago, would help strengthen friendship of the two close neighbours. Hasina paid homage at the memorial to Mahatma Gandhi in Rajghat on Monday, before returning to her hotel, the ITC Maurya, where external affairs minister SM Krishna met with her. Hasina then visited Indian president Pratibha Patil at the latter's official residence. She then returned to her hotel where Indian finance minister Pranab Mukherjee and opposition party leader Sushama Swaraj visited her. During the meeting, the Indian leaders praised Hasina for her role in establishing democracy in Bangladesh, Azad said. He said Hasina also recalled India's contribution to the achievement of Bangladesh's independence and expressed her gratitude. Hasina also reminisced about independence hero Sheikh Mujibur Rahman's visit to India in January 1972 before his homecoming from Pakistan. Foreign minister Dipu Moni, water resources minister Ramesh Chandra Sen, advisor to the prime minister HT Imam, among others, were present during meetings. Hasina's sister Sheikh Rehana, son Sajib Wazed Joy were also with her. bd
